# $archon_name — a Demiurge-minted Archon

Generated by Demiurge's `claude-sdk` reference adapter (ADR 0005). The spec
(`archon.agf.yaml`) is the source of truth; this project only serves it.

## Run

    uv run python server.py --port 9999

The agent card is served at the A2A well-known path
(`/.well-known/agent-card.json`) for discovery; delegation happens over A2A
JSON-RPC at `/`. The server boots and serves its card without LLM auth.

Delegated tasks execute the spec's `agf.react` policy on the Claude Agent SDK.
Authentication follows the SDK's normal rules (`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`, or a
Claude Code login). When deployed via `demiurge deploy`, a set
`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY_DEMIURGE` is passed through to the Archon as
`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` so Demiurge's spend stays on its own key.

## Tool grants

MCP servers declared in the spec's `action_space.mcp_servers` carry portable
`server_ref` identities; mapping those to real connection details is the
runtime owner's job (as the Agent Format spec assigns it). To wire them up:

1. Copy `mcp-servers.example.json` (generated when the spec declares grants)
   to `mcp-servers.json`.
2. Replace each entry with the real connection config for that server, in
   Claude Agent SDK `mcp_servers` format — e.g.
   `{"command": "npx", "args": ["-y", "some-mcp-server"], "env": {}}` or
   `{"type": "http", "url": "https://..."}`.

At boot, `server.py` maps each granted alias onto `ClaudeAgentOptions.mcp_servers`
and allows exactly the spec's `allowed_tools` (`mcp__<alias>__<tool>`; a grant
without `allowed_tools` allows the whole server). Grants with no entry in
`mcp-servers.json` are skipped — the Archon runs without them. Keep
`mcp-servers.json` out of version control if it holds secrets.
